最佳解答: 
             I don't know how type in Chinese, so let me explain it in English, if you don't mind!  

Heat transfer has 3 basic forms: Conduction, Convection and Radiation.  
However, your question is not about heat transfer, but it does use the concept of Convection a little. 

As you know, combustion need fuel and air.  When a candle burns, the fuel is the wax.  Wax needs a certain temperature to ignite and burn.  When it burns you need to supply air.  Naturally, when it burns, it will create convection around the flame (due to the hot air rises and pull in the surrounding air, this is the only part that is related to heat transfer: convection).   

When you blow the flame gently, you will supply more air to help the combustion, so the flame will get bigger, due to more air, more combustion, more fuel will be drawn into.   

However, if you blow it too hard, as I have said earlier, to ignite and burn the wax, you need a certain temperature.  Therefore, when you blow too hard, you not only supply more air, but also cool down the temperature (by more air) to a point that it can NO LONGER burn wax and result in putting off the flame.   

Therefore, the point is NOT how gentle you shall blow the candle flame, but how much cold air it can sustain with the flame it has.  In other words, if the flame can generate enough of heat to sustain the cold air being blown to it, then it can help the flame, otherwise it will put it off.  Therefore, if you have a huge candle with a huge wick, then you can even bring an electrical fan to blow it.  It will not be put off, but be careful with the flame !  

If you have trouble to understand English, I might be able to have someone to translate it for you.           


